          <h2 id="compliance-tips">Staying Compliant in St. Catharines</h2>
          <p>With the demerit system, every violation counts. Here's how to stay compliant:</p>

          <ul class="tips-list">
            <li><span class="tip-icon">1</span> <strong>Get your electrical certificate first.</strong> This requirement catches many hosts off-guard. Schedule a licensed electrical contractor before starting your application.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">2</span> <strong>Track your demerit points.</strong> Know where you stand at all times. Keep records of any violations or warnings. Two moderate violations can trigger a suspension.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">3</span> <strong>Set up 1-hour response capability.</strong> Designate an agent who can actually respond within 1 hour. Don't name someone who might be unavailable when needed.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">4</span> <strong>Document your principal residence.</strong> Keep records proving you live at the property 183+ days per year - utility bills, tax filings, driver's license.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">5</span> <strong>Prevent noise violations.</strong> Noise complaints accumulate demerit points quickly. Set clear quiet hours and communicate them to every guest.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">6</span> <strong>Maintain your insurance.</strong> An insurance lapse can trigger violations. Set up auto-renewal and calendar reminders.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">7</span> <strong>Remember the 2-year renewal.</strong> St. Catharines has shorter license terms than some cities. Mark your renewal date and start the process early.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">8</span> <strong>Consider mid-term for flexibility.</strong> 29+ day bookings aren't STRs. Use this for longer stays or during slower seasons.</li>
          </ul>

